Do you remember that? We here on the stage where sadistically enjoying the cruelty of timetabling a gathering so early on your first Monday morning. You were nervously eyeing each other and thinking how will it ever get along with all these strangers and not suspecting that the strangers were looking at you and thinking you were pretty strange too? Well today there are far fewer strangers in the room, but these people that you now know so well are not the same as they were on that first Monday. Nobody here is because not only has the world altered around us and it has very powerfully, especially in these last two years. But education, and especially higher education is all about change and it always has been. Now, some people don't agree with this, and of course it's easy or lazy to characterize any institution, especially one with prominent traditions as we have as stuck in the past. You know the old question. Probably that goes how many Saint Andrews professors does it take to change a light bulb? To which the answer is change? In fact, the scholars that you see here before you on the stage live for change is our reason that our very vocation is to shake and reform the paradigms that people use to decode the universe and to pass that calling on to you. Through your studies, you've of course acquired an understanding of your subjects, but you also now have a perspective on the wider world that was built partly upon the work of this academic community, which in turn is inflicted by the intellectual pioneers who came before us, as well as those with whom we're in touch all around the world. Now I'm well qualified to speak with authority on this point, because as you can see with your own eyes, and as I've just confirmed by my reference to a light bulb joke, I am quite old. In fact, to underline this point more forcefully, I shall inform you for future reference that the correct answer to any light bulb changing question is that it takes 51 one to swap the bulb and 50 to do this and switch it on because many hands make light work. But also that everything we read if we do it open mindedly and analytically helps us to reframe the way that we see the entire world. Even more pertinently, to me at the time I found female writers who could entirely revise how we thought about gender equality and difference. When I came back here as a lecturer in the 1990s, I witnessed the students who took my courses go through the same type of radical revelations in relation to decolonization and ethnicity through the postcolonial literature we studied together. Now today all these years later, the concepts that seemed so revolutionary to me or my students are relatively commonplace for many young people. New critical perspectives on sex, gender, race, and empire have changed into established ones and are part of public consciousness. Now, I have absolutely no wish to overstate the academy's role in changes like this, and I certainly don't feel complacent as if our work. We're all done. It emphatically is not. My point is simply that universities have helped to alter our thinking and change society. Social scientists like Professor Phoenix are honorary graduate and her laureato Dr Sangara as you heard, have made brilliant contributions to these developments, and so have researchers, teachers, and students of languages, literature, psychology, science, neuroscience, film, philosophy, and so on, and so on, all of whom ensure that universities play a systematic role in social change. There are some in our society who fear and dislike change, many of whom seem to believe that universities should exist only to pass on static information and enable safe discoveries.
